{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17618237","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17618237"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:20:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:20:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16504"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16504","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16504"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9195"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74778"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9195","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9195"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16504"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60264"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"8508"},{"type":"tags","id":"8509"},{"type":"tags","id":"10372"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21811"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21814"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74778","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74778"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EPeripheral nerves contain different types of nerve fibres that can be classified based on their size, conduction velocity, and myelination status.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following nerve fibre types is unmyelinated?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Type Ia fibres","Type Ib fibres","Type II fibres","Type III fibres","Type IV fibres"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003EType IV fibres\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as C fibres. These are unmyelinated fibres that conduct pain, temperature, and crude touch sensations at relatively slow velocities (0.5-2.0 m/s).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other fibre types are all myelinated:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType Ia fibres\u003C/strong\u003E are large, heavily myelinated fibres that innervate muscle spindles (annulospiral endings)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType Ib fibres\u003C/strong\u003E are also heavily myelinated and innervate Golgi tendon organs\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType II fibres\u003C/strong\u003E are moderately myelinated and serve touch and pressure sensations\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType III fibres\u003C/strong\u003E are thinly myelinated and conduct fast pain and cold temperature sensations\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMyelination increases conduction velocity by allowing saltatory conduction between nodes of Ranvier. The absence of myelin in Type IV fibres explains their slower conduction velocity.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Type IV nerve fibers (C fibers) are unmyelinated and conduct pain, temperature, and crude touch sensations.","Types Ia, Ib, II, and III nerve fibres are all myelinated and serve different sensory and motor functions.","Unmyelinated fibres conduct signals more slowly than myelinated fibres."],"references":["Arcilla CK, Tadi P. Neuroanatomy, Unmyelinated Nerve Fibers. 2023 Jan 2. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32119348.","Jankowski MP, Rau KK, Ekmann KM, Anderson CE, Koerber HR. Comprehensive phenotyping of group III and IV muscle afferents in mouse. J Neurophysiol. 2013 May;109(9):2374-81. doi: 10.1152/jn.01067.2012. Epub 2013 Feb 20. Erratum in: J Neurophysiol. 2015 Jan 15;113(2):677. doi: 10.1152/jn.z9k-2807-corr.2014. PMID: 23427306; PMCID: PMC3652219.","Yam MF, Loh YC, Tan CS, Khadijah Adam S, Abdul Manan N, Basir R. General Pathways of Pain Sensation and the Major Neurotransmitters Involved in Pain Regulation. Int J Mol Sci. 2018 Jul 24;19(8):2164. doi: 10.3390/ijms19082164. PMID: 30042373; PMCID: PMC6121522.","Singh, V. (2024).\u00a0Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022).\u00a0The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60264"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16504"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60264","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60264"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-26T23:27:31+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-26T23:53:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9195"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74778"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retri